<html><head><meta charset='utf-8'><title>Netflix Clone Report Max 50 Pages</title></head><body><pre style='font-family:Calibri,Consolas,monospace; font-size:11pt; white-space:pre-wrap;'># Netflix Clone Project Report (Max 50 Pages Version)

## 1. Introduction
This project is a full-stack Netflix Clone developed to simulate the core experience of a modern OTT platform. It includes account authentication, content discovery, trailer playback, advanced search, personalized list management, subscription management, role-based administration, and payment verification.

The implementation is built as a monorepo with:
1. React frontend (`frontend`)
2. Node.js + Express backend (`backend`)
3. MongoDB data layer (Mongoose models)

The system is designed for both demonstration and extension, with modular APIs and clearly separated concerns between UI, business logic, and persistence.

---

## 2. Objectives
The primary objectives of this project are:

1. Build a Netflix-like user interface and streaming discovery flow.
2. Implement secure authentication and profile management.
3. Provide personalized experiences (My List, settings persistence).
4. Support role-based controls for admin and superadmin operations.
5. Integrate a payment-based subscription update mechanism.
6. Keep architecture modular and maintainable for future scaling.

Secondary objectives:
1. Build responsive layout for mobile and desktop.
2. Handle service failures gracefully with fallback content behavior.
3. Maintain code readability using componentization and controller separation.

---

## 3. Analysis

### 3.1 Problem Statement
Users expect streaming services to provide:
1. Smooth browsing
2. Personalized recommendations/lists
3. Fast search
4. Account and subscription control
5. Responsive design

Simple clones usually fail because they are static UIs without robust backend logic. This project addresses that by introducing backend-driven data, user management, and payment verification.

### 3.2 Proposed Solution
The solution integrates:
1. React SPA with route protection and lazy-loaded components.
2. REST API backend for auth/movies/admin/payment.
3. MongoDB models for users and movies.
4. TMDB integration for dynamic content/trailer fetch.
5. Razorpay signature verification for payment trust.

### 3.3 Feasibility
1. Technical: MERN-style architecture is suitable and proven.
2. Operational: Monorepo allows smooth local development and deployment progression.
3. Economic: Open-source stack minimizes cost.
4. Time: Modular structure supports phased delivery.

### 3.4 Requirements Summary
Functional:
1. Register/login/logout
2. Browse movies/TV categories
3. Search/filter/sort content
4. Manage My List
5. Edit profile/settings/password
6. Manage subscriptions and roles by privileges
7. Payment order + verification flow

Non-functional:
1. Responsive UI
2. Error handling and fallback behavior
3. Maintainability
4. Security checks on privileged actions

---

## 4. Project Modules

### 4.1 Frontend Module
Location: `frontend/src`

Key responsibilities:
1. Routing and protected pages
2. UI rendering and interactions
3. Local state and persistence (`localStorage`)
4. API communication via dedicated client files

Main files:
1. `frontend/src/App.js`
2. `frontend/src/api/authApi.js`
3. `frontend/src/api/moviesApi.js`
4. `frontend/src/api/adminApi.js`
5. `frontend/src/api/paymentApi.js`
6. `frontend/src/components/*`

### 4.2 Backend Module
Location: `backend/src`

Key responsibilities:
1. Request routing
2. Validation and business logic
3. Database interactions
4. External integration calls (TMDB, Razorpay)

Main files:
1. `backend/src/app.js`
2. `backend/src/controllers/*.js`
3. `backend/src/routes/*.js`
4. `backend/src/models/*.js`

### 4.3 Authentication Module
Features:
1. Register user
2. Login user
3. Update profile
4. Update password

Security:
1. Password hashing with `bcryptjs`
2. Input validation and status-specific responses

### 4.4 Content Module
Features:
1. Movie catalog fetch
2. TMDB trailer fetch
3. Filter/search by query
4. Local seed fallback when remote unavailable

### 4.5 Admin Module
Features:
1. List users
2. Change subscription plans/status
3. Change user roles (superadmin)
4. Delete users (superadmin)

### 4.6 Payment Module
Features:
1. Create Razorpay order
2. Verify signature via HMAC
3. Update subscription upon successful verification

---

## 5. Use Case Model

### Actors
1. Guest
2. User
3. Admin
4. Superadmin
5. TMDB API
6. Razorpay API

### Core Use Cases
1. Register/Login
2. Browse catalog and watch trailers
3. Search/filter/sort content
4. Maintain My List
5. Update profile/settings/password
6. Manage subscriptions/payments
7. Manage users and roles (authorized actors only)

### Role Matrix
1. Guest: Register/Login only
2. User: Browse/search/list/profile/subscription
3. Admin: User list + subscription management
4. Superadmin: All admin actions + role updates + account deletion

---

## 6. Implementation Details

### 6.1 Technology Stack
Frontend:
1. React
2. React Router
3. Axios + Fetch APIs
4. CSS/Tailwind-style utility classes

Backend:
1. Node.js
2. Express
3. Mongoose
4. bcryptjs
5. node-fetch

External Integrations:
1. TMDB for dynamic content/trailer metadata
2. Razorpay for payments

### 6.2 Frontend Routing
Implemented routes include:
1. `/`
2. `/movies`
3. `/tv-shows`
4. `/new-popular`
5. `/my-list`
6. `/search`
7. `/login`
8. `/profile`
9. `/help`
10. `/settings`
11. `/subscription`
12. `/admin`
13. `/super-admin`

Route guards:
1. `ProtectedRoute` for authenticated pages
2. `RoleRoute` for minimum-role pages

### 6.3 Backend API Endpoints
Auth:
1. `POST /api/auth/register`
2. `POST /api/auth/login`
3. `PUT /api/auth/profile`
4. `PUT /api/auth/password`

Movies:
1. `GET /api/movies`
2. `GET /api/movies/:id`
3. `GET /api/movies/tmdb-trailer/:type/:id`
4. `POST /api/movies`
5. `PUT /api/movies/:id`
6. `DELETE /api/movies/:id`

Admin:
1. `GET /api/admin/users`
2. `PUT /api/admin/users/:id/subscription`
3. `PUT /api/admin/users/:id/role`
4. `DELETE /api/admin/users/:id`

Payments:
1. `POST /api/payments/create-order`
2. `POST /api/payments/verify`

### 6.4 Database Models
`User` model:
1. Identity fields
2. Credentials (`passwordHash`)
3. Role (`user/admin/superadmin`)
4. Nested subscription details

`Movie` model:
1. Title/description/category
2. Type (`movie/series`)
3. Media URLs
4. Search text index

### 6.5 Reliability and Error Handling
1. Backend validates DB connectivity before critical operations.
2. TMDB calls use timeout/retry/cooldown logic.
3. Movie data falls back to local seed where needed.
4. API clients surface meaningful error messages.

### 6.6 Performance Considerations
1. Lazy loading for heavy UI components.
2. Deferred search input processing to keep typing smooth.
3. Structured filtering/sorting via memoized computations.

